								 <div class="black16" align="center"><b>SUB-BRAND</b> </div>
								 <br><br>
					
The Sub-Brand is a second brand that is used to characterize a group of products or services that are considered significant enough of a departure from the original brand to stand-alone. 
<br><br>
After you read this section, you may decide that you do not need a Sub-Brand.   If that is the case, you have two choices with this positioning element. You can scroll down to the bottom of this page and click on the “I don’t need a Sub-Brand” link, 
or you can click the "I Have an Existing Sub-Brand" link. 
<br><br>
Whatever the case, please let us share the secrets we have learned from our work with Sub-Brands. 

<br><br>
Unlike the brand, the Sub-Brand’s primary function is not as a product identifier, but quite the reverse.  Its function is 80% to add character and 20% to serve as an identifier whose function is to pull a group of products together under the established parent brand. That is not to infer that the 20% is not important. but the Sub-Brand's primary function is adding remarkability through appropriate character. 
<br><br>
If you read the Brand section you are familiar with the four characteristics of a great brand name. The characteristics of a great Sub-brand name are the same with one significant difference. Characterizing is moved from the bottom of the list to the top. In fact the sole purpose of the Sub-Brand name is to provide character. 
<br><br>
CHARACTERIZING, SHORT, POETIC, MEMORABLE.
<br><br>

It’s easy to see that Go-Gurt has character. Let’s look at how well it conforms to Short, Poetic and Memorable. SHORT is a virtue for a reason you may not suspect. If a Sub-Brand name is short, it will accommodate being made prominent at the impact point. That may be a web site, a brochure, a retail shelf, an ad etc, etc. Often it will be so prominent that it will become a key graphic. Go-Gurt is a perfect example of combining character and designing it into a key graphic.
<br><br>
For our purposes let’s assume that POETIC refers to how smooth and rhythmic the Sub-Brand is pronounced. This effects how easily it is  used in a conversation. These poetic features make it easy for target consumers to integrate it into their psyche. Beyond their general awareness, it also facilitates easy recognition of what it now stands for. What it now stands for is what you communicate in your Selling Proposition. Simply pronounce Go-Gurt a couple of times and you will get just how poetic it is.
<br><br>
MEMORABLE is very strongly related to poetics in that typically highly poetic words are also easy to remember. Memorable is a virtue worth having in a Sub-Brand name and well worth pursuing. Again simply repeat Go-Gurt a couple of times and you will quickly get a sense of how memorable it is likely to be.


<br><br>
When Yoplait decided to sell yogurt to kids they had no choice. Kids were simply not going to eat Yoplait yogurt.  Put it in a tube and characterize it in a fun way and you have a huge opportunity. Notice the prominence and character of the word GoGurt. Think of it on its first day in the supermarket and you will see its Remarkability. 

