For years, marketers avoided Sub-Brands.  The insisted advertising support would be needed to make them a household word.  They rationalized that the only function of a brand name was recognition and they applied this same thinking to the Sub-Brand.  In truth, recognition has never been the function of a Sub-Brand; it doesn’t need to be a  household word.  It is just a device to heavily characterize one or more key products within the larger brand. i.e. Doritos chips produced by Frito-Lay.  
<br><br>
Examples of Sub-Brands exist in all categories.  The Microsoft Xbox, the Apple iPod, Google Earth, and Yoplait Gogurt are but a few obvious references.  There are three marketing circumstances when creating a Sub-Brand that will be to your advantage.  
 <br><br>
The more compelling circumstance occurs when the new product or service is going to be supported with significant advertising and promotion aside from that of the existing products.  Such is the case with the Xbox.  It just makes sense to give target consumers a Sub-Brand to refer to it specifically. 
    								<br>
									<img src="images/xbox.jpg">
								 <br><br>   
					 
					
Another circumstance occurs when the new product or service is drastically different from your existing products in the line.  As was the case with Nintendo Game Cube, you can see that it needs to be characterized – it bares no relationship to its parent brand. 
   								<br>
									<img src="images/game_cube.jpg">
								 <br><br>   
					 
					
Take a look at your product offerings.  If you have more than one, you should consider uniquely characterizing one or more of them with as Sub-Brand.  It could be a huge advantage. 
